1. Introduction

This study aims to understand how and whether rotten tomatoes ratings will influence the profitability of Hollywood movies. To be specific the question is whether the ratings and genre of movies will affect the percentage of profitability for Hollywood movies.

We have data from different genres of various profitable Hollywood movies in 2011 and its corresponding variables that describe it. The data set contains the rotten tomatoes ratings and profitability of the movies, both of which are measured in percentage. The data was obtained from the orignial source itself which was the information is beautiful website, in which you can access it through a title named Hollywood Budgets1.

We decided to focus on the Profitability as our outcome variable in order to make this report more concise. We included two explanatory variables in this analysis: the rotten tomatoes ratings, and genre of movies, five levels, Action, Comedy, Drama, Horror and Other, which was 10 levels before data wrangling. We had to remove the first row of the data set because it displayed only the units of measurement of the columns. We had to remove the percentage sign from the values under the probability variable and convert the values of probability and rotten tomatoes variables from string to numerical to conduct exploratory analysis.

Here is a snapshot of 5 randomly chosen rows of the data set well use:

film profitability rotten_tomatoes genre lead_studio

2. Exploratory data analysis

We had an original sample size of 143 movies. These were observations, where there were no information available in its columns like profitability, genre, rotten_tomatoes, and lead_studio. The observation that can be identified as Average in the film category, is not a film but the row used to calculate the average of the numerical variables. This observation was not useful as it only partly collected average values of the whole data set and was placed in between categorical values which could be easily misunderstood. Also the first row of the original data only displayed the corresponding units of measurement of the variables. Therefore, those 4 observations had to be ignored for further exploratory and numerical analysis. Unfortunately, no information was provided as to why some movies had missing values and most didnt, so we cannot comment on the impact dropping these missing cases has on our results.

Our total sample size was 139 (Table 1). The mean of the profitability of movies was greatest for Horror movies (n = 16, \(\bar{x}\) = 852.9, sd = 1795.1), and lowest for Action movies (n = 31, \(\bar{x}\) = 240.4, sd = 152.5).

The rotten tomatoes ratings of movies ranged from 4% to 97% (\(\bar{x}\) = 54.6, sd = 26.8).

3. Multiple linear regression

3.1 Methods

The components of our multiple linear regression model are the following:

  • Outcome variable \(y\) = Profitability of Movies (%)
  • Numerical explanatory variable \(x_1\) = Rotten Tomatoes Ratings of Movies (%)
  • Categorical explanatory variable \(x_2\) = Genre of the Movies

where the unit of analysis are the movies, given that each row in our dataset corresponds to a unique film.

3.2 Model Results

Table 2. Regression table of parallel slopes model of Profitability as a function of percentage of rotten tomatoes and genre of movies.

term estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
intercept -14.428 148.289 -0.097 0.923 -307.738 278.883
rotten_tomatoes 5.668 2.153 2.633 0.009 1.410 9.926

3.3 Interpreting the regression table

The regression equation for Profitability is the following:

\[ \begin{aligned}\widehat {profitability} =& b_{0} + b_{rt} \cdot rt + b_{cmdy} \cdot 1_{is\ cmdy}(x_2) + b_{drm} \cdot 1_{is\ drm}(x_2) + b_{hor} \cdot 1_{is\ hor}(x_2) + b_{oth} \cdot 1_{is\ oth}(x_2) \\ =& -14.428 + 5.668 \cdot rt + 52.644 \cdot 1_{is\ cmdy}(x_2) - 91.930 \cdot 1_{is\ drm}(x_2) + 637.124 \cdot 1_{is\ hor}(x_2) + 45.645 \cdot 1_{is\ oth}(x_2) \end{aligned} \]

  • The intercept (\(b_0\) = -14.428) represents the Profitability when there is zero percent rotten tomatoes ratings and the genre is action movies (Table 2).
  • The estimate for the slope for rotten tomatoes (\(b_{rt}\) = 5.668) is the associated change in profitability depending on the rotten tomatoes ratings. Based on this estimate, for every one percentage point increase in the rotten tomatoes ratings of movies, there was an associated increase in Profitability of an average 5.668 points.
  • The estimate for comedy movies (\(b_{cmdy}\) = 52.644), drama movies (\(b_{drm}\) = -91.93), horror movies (\(b_{hor}\) = 637.124), and other movies (\(b_{oth}\) = 45.645) are the offsets in intercept relative to the baseline groups, action movies, intercept (Table 2). In other words, on average comedy movies score 52.644 points more than action movies while drama movies scored on average 91.93 lower (the same logic is applied to the rest of the movie genres).

Thus the five regression lines have equations:

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Action movies (in red)}: \widehat {profitability} =& -14.428 + 5.668 \cdot rt\\ \text{Comedy movies (in dark green)}: \widehat {profitability} =& 38.216 + 5.668 \cdot rt\\ \text{Drama movies (in light green)}: \widehat {profitability} =& -106.358 + 5.668 \cdot rt\\ \text{Horror movies (in blue)}: \widehat {profitability} =& 622.696 + 5.668 \cdot rt\\ \text{Other movies (in pink)}: \widehat {profitability} =& 31.217 + 5.668 \cdot rt \end{aligned} \]
